  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "A progressive, permanent flexion of the digits of the hand due to myofibroblastic disease of the palmar and digital fascia\nIt most commonly affects the fourth and fifth digits\nUnilateral contracture predominately affects the right side but bilateral involvement is common",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Initially, painless nodules are present longitudinally along the lines of tension\nContracture deformities within fascial bands of the hand occur when the nodules form cords\nBlanching of the digit on extension\nProximal to the nodules, the cords are painless\nPits and grooves may be present\nThe knuckle pads over the PIP joints may be tender\nIf the plantar fascia is involved, this indicates more severe disease (Ledderhose disease)\nThe tabletop test (Hueston) is performed by having the patient attempt to place the palm flat on the exam table. If there is any flexion contracture deformity, the patient will be unable to straighten the fingers, resulting in a positive test.\n[1]",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
